'''Engineering cybernetics''' or '''technical cybernetics''', established by [[H.S. Tsien]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Tsien  |first= Hsue-Shen |date=1954 |title=Engineering Cybernetics  |url= |location= |publisher=McGraw-Hill |page= |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> is a field of [[cybernetics]], which deals with the question of [[control engineering]] of [[mechatronic]] systems as well as chemical or [[biological systems]]. It is used to control and predict the behaviour of such a system; see [[control theory]].

An example of engineering cybernetics is a device designed in the mid-1960s by [[General Electric Company]]. Referred to as a CAM ([[Walking truck|cybernetic anthropomorphous machine]]), this [[machine]] was designed for use by the [[US Army]] ground troops. Operated by one man in a "cockpit" at the front end, the machine's "legs" steps were duplicates of the leg movements of the harnessed operator.

