'''Richard Arthur''' (25 October 1865 – 21 May 1932) was an Australian politician, social reformer and medical practitioner.

==Early life==
Arthur was born in [[Aldershot]], Hampshire, England and educated at [[Dover College]].  He received a [[Master of Arts]] from the [[University of St Andrews]] (1885) and a [[Bachelor of Medicine and Surgery|MB ChB]] from the [[University of Edinburgh]] (1888).  He worked in the slums of Edinburgh, but contracted [[typhoid fever]].  He met and married his wife in Australia in 1890.  He returned to Europe and studied [[hypnotism]] in Paris, which earned him an [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] from the University of Edinburgh in 1891<ref>{{Cite thesis |last=Arthur |first=Richard |date=1891 |title=Hypnotism and its therapeutic uses |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/23687 |language=en |publisher=University of Edinburgh}}</ref>.  After again becoming ill working in the slums of London, he returned to Australia and established a practice in the Sydney suburb of [[Mosman, New South Wales|Mosman]], specialising in eye, ear-nose-and-throat, and dental work.  He was a director of the [[Royal Prince Alfred Hospital]] from 1917 to 1920 and from 1927 to 1931 and of [[Sydney Hospital]] from 1924 to 1932.<ref name=adb>{{cite web
  | first=Michael 
  | last=Roe  
  | title =Arthur, Richard (1865–1932)  
  | publisher=[[Australian National University]]
  | work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]
  | url =http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A070106b.htm
  | accessdate =12 April 2007}}</ref>

==Political career==
Arthur was elected in 1904 to the [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly]] as member for [[electoral district of Middle Harbour|Middle Harbour]], representing the [[Liberal Reform Party (Australia)|Liberal and Reform Party]].  In December 1912, he became the inaugural president of the [[Eugenics Society of New South Wales]].<ref>[http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/15382345 The Sydney Morning Herald, 11 December 1912]</ref> He became an early advocate of child endowment in 1916 and was a strong supporter of closer settlement and [[Immigration to Australia|assisted immigration]] to reduce the Japanese threat.  From 1920 to 1927, he represented [[electoral district of North Shore|North Shore]].  He was chairman of the 1923 [[Royal Commission]] on Lunacy Law and Administration and, as a [[Eugenics|eugenicist]], recommended special training and institutions for "defectives".   He represented [[electoral district of Mosman|Mosman]] from 1927 to 1932 and was Minister for Public Health from 1927 to 1930 during the [[Thomas Bavin|Bavin]] Government,<ref name=nsw>{{cite web
  | title =Dr Richard Arthur (1865–1932)  
  | work=Members of Parliament 
  | publisher=[[Parliament of New South Wales]]
  | url =http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/members.nsf/1fb6ebed995667c2ca256ea100825164/b1403accf428ea00ca256e200003ebc2?OpenDocument
  | accessdate =16 April 2007}}</ref>  but he failed to carry a mental defectives bill.<ref name=adb/>

Arthur died in [[Mosman, New South Wales|Mosman]] and was  survived by his wife, son and two daughters.<ref name=adb/>

