'''Secular arm''', in [[ecclesiastical law]], refers to the legal authority of the civil power, the State, or any [[Laity|lay]] authority, invoked by the Church to punish offenders in cases properly belonging to the jurisdiction of the Church. In the [[Middle Ages]] especially in Inquisition trials for [[heresy]], or grave immorality, ecclesiastical courts delivered convicted clerical and lay offenders over to the secular arm to administer severe capital punishments. The phrase "[[Spanish Inquisition#Sentencing|relaxed]] to the secular arm" was used by the [[Spanish Inquistion]] to describe the handover of the condemned heretic.
The medieval Latin phrase 'brachium seculare' was translated first into late Middle English.<ref>The Oxford Dictionary of Phrase and Fable, Religion</ref>
==Background== Introduced circa 1180–1250 at the time of the [[Albigensian Crusade]], the church inquisitors delivered a [[Cathar]] heretic, or any heretic, to the secular arm, to be burnt at the stake. Under [[canon law]] church tribunals had no jurisdiction to impose penalties involving mutilation or death.<ref>Encyclopedia of the Middle Ages p.260</ref> Notably the contrary circumstance of appeal by individuals to the secular authorities to interfere with, or hinder, the process of ecclesiastical jurisdiction was until recently punished in the [[Roman Catholic (term)|Roman Catholic]] [[Catholic Church|Church]] by [[excommunication]].<ref>The Concise Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church (3 ed.)p.532</ref>
==Sources== [https://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/dictionary/index.cfm?id=36369 Catholic Culture] [http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803100451648 The Oxford Dictionary of Phrase and Fable, Religion]
